My favourite rainbows are the shy ones. They do not stretch across the whole sky like a giant bridge. No, these are small, quiet arcs that hide behind the old oak tree in my garden.

They appear only after a quick, warm shower in July. The sun peeks out, just for a second, and there it is. A tiny curve of colour, sitting right on the wet grass. It looks like a puddle of paint spilled by a giant.

I love these little rainbows because they feel like secrets. The big ones are for everyone to see, but the small ones feel special, just for me. I tiptoe closer, careful not to step on the dew. The colours are soft: a hint of red, a touch of yellow, and a gentle blue. They fade away quickly, vanishing before I can even count them properly.

It is a bit sad, but also exciting. I never know when the next shy rainbow will visit. I keep my eyes on the garden, waiting for that tiny flash of light. It reminds me that magic is often small and quiet, hiding in plain sight. I smile, knowing I am the only one who saw it. That makes it even more wonderful. [end of text]


